{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aa15f42d-b077-4d21-9f84-09caa101e892","content":"In .NET 10 MAUI, the iOS-specific `UseSafeArea` was replaced with a **cross-platform** `SafeAreaRegions` property on `Page`.\n\n**Before (.NET 9):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\n**After (.NET 10):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage SafeAreaRegions=\"All\">\n```\n\nThat's it — no platform namespace needed. `SafeAreaRegions` accepts `All`, `None`, or specific edges. It also works on Android (for cutouts/gesture areas), so you get consistent behavior across platforms.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5acae015-ecae-4f9d-8060-18edaf1d1eb4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI migration issue from .NET 9 to .NET 10 regarding safe area handling on iOS. This is a known breaking change in .NET 10 MAUI.\n\nIn .NET 10, the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` attached property was removed/deprecated in favor of a new cross-platform approach using `SafeAreaRegions` property on `Page`.\n\nThe new approach in .NET 10 uses:\n- `Page.SafeAreaRegions` property which is cross-platform (works on iOS and Android)\n- Values like `SafeAreaRegions.All`, `SafeAreaRegions.None`, etc.\n\n\n- By default, pages no longer automatically respect safe areas, so you need to explicitly set this property\n- You can set it to `All` to respect all safe area insets, `None` to ignore them, or specific regions\n\nWriting the XAML example...","outputTokens":706,"requestId":"942B:840A1:137D604:15D80CF:6A066E7A"},"id":"7b343b27-a75c-42b5-a072-e089877a1f9f","timestamp":"2026-05-15T00:53:27.901Z","parentId":"ae6ca162-67a3-40cb-80ea-6a66d81af563"}
